I’m sorry for this random stream of consciousness. I’m just feeling a little sad, lonely and tired of only having the amazing little people on my phone to turn to when I need help, advice and support.

I just wish there were more real people in my life I could talk to who get it.

I went to Pride back in September. I was there as a uniformed service, putting on a stand and providing medical cover. I guess I felt almost a little sad that I couldn’t just be one of the “crowd” that day. But equally I likely wouldn’t have gone otherwise due to anxiety.

I think a lot of this stems from the fact I did everything to do with transition online throughout the pandemic. I explored myself online, I came out online, I get my HRT online, I speak to other trans people online. Not once have I done anything locally other than one pride.

And yes, a part of me dreams of that cute relationship I see so many people on here have… The transfem meets transfem and get together sort of story. 

I don’t want to seem salty and please don’t take it this way. I don’t mean to upset anyone. I guess I’m just a little jealous?

I don’t think I feel lonely, but more that I just would like to feel a part of a community in real life. 

Not just on Twitter. 

I literally cannot think of anyone who I see regularly who is close to my age and also transfem and also local. No one.

I’m starting to wonder how other trans people find each other locally. Like, I know that I can’t be the only trans girl in my local area. I live in a relatively big ish city with good transport connections. Yet I feel like I’m the only trans girl in my age range in the area.
@Becka_Kinchin I do the same. Wack the volume all the way up with bass boost on. It feels so good.

I found my phone eventually. In my shed at the bottom of the garden. I don’t remember going down to my shed in the last couple of hours. But I must have done because I’ve done the task which involved me going down to the shed. And… well… my phone was there.

Got a notification on my watch. Went to find my phone to respond to the notification but I’ve just spent the last hour searching for it. Eventually logging into my wifi controller (because I have enterprise grade wifi at home) and working out which access point it was closest to.

It is 04:48 in the morning and I just managed to book a theory test for driving large vehicles. Finally I’m able to start making steps to further my career.

(3/4)

@G6ZTZ I’ve not thought about going private but it definitely keeps crossing my mind. I just don’t know if I could raise enough. It’s likely in the 10’s of thousands at a guess.

@AlyssaGambone Someone warned me right after my egg cracked when I’d started joining communities online that dysphoria will only get worse for a while. And that some euphoric moments will happen but dysphoria would be the main theme. 

That was the most accurate thing I’ve ever heard.

All this brought about by me having a very short dream-turned-nightmare about bottom surgery and not actually being able to get it. 

I hate this. Hormones are great but my dysphoria has been wild recently. Especially about stuff that only surgery can fix.

Honestly deciding to go for private care with @GenderGP was possibly the best decision I made having found out about the wait times back when I was referred. 

It’s still gut wrenching to know how long that waiting list is. For me and those who are only just going on it.

I just worked out from some very basic napkin maths based on the current waiting times on the Charing Cross Gender Identity Clinic website that although I’ve been on the waiting list for two years I still have 5 and a half more years to wait.

I am confident. I am brave. I am Chloe and I am transgender. Nothing can change those things.

He said that he admires my confidence and could never do the same.

But then he explained that I’m the same in a slightly different way. 

Every day… literally every day I walk into work or out in public feeling exactly the same. Feeling anxious about what could happen for being my true self. Being anxious of the possibility of transphobia.

One of my best friends said something to me last night that really hit me. 

As a police officer he runs into complex and dangerous situations where he doesn’t know what is going to happen. 

I think he is extremely brave and confident. Something I don’t think I could ever be.

Today the team are wonderful too. Unfortunately doctors messed up so I’m in a lot of pain as didn’t have painkillers for ages. The nurse has been amazing but so busy. Being a patient is hard but knowing how busy they are I do feel like I’m more of a burden.

Overnight the team were great and really helpful. I was allowed a small bite to eat but there wasn’t much point as it didn’t stay in me for long. A change of bedding and some stronger painkillers along with some anti sickness at 3am then back to sleep.

Initially I overheard someone referencing me and using masculine pronouns. I assume this is because they had only seen my medical record which still unfortunately shows me as male. They used feminine pronouns once they spoke to me in person.

I asked for more privacy in this bay. Simply because I’m surrounded by 5 ladies over the age of 60 or 70 who when I was wheeled in all had that sort of “look” to them. I’ve had the curtains drawn around my bed since. I’m glad as I’ve heard some very “Karen” conversations.

The Doctors were very understanding, didn’t question anything transgender related unless it was relevant.

I was then asked where I would like to be placed. In a male or female bay. (With other patients). For non binary people this would be amazing. I chose female obviously.

Moved up to a ward where I had an absolutely amazing Healthcare Assistant. He asked me if there was anything specific or special they could do for me given that I am trans. I said not right now. They put me in a room on my own so I had privacy.

I was in a lot of pain and felt really rubbish. I mentioned I was transgender due to the infection area but the doctors and nurses went out of their way to make sure I was comfortable and treated just like any other lady in that department. They did give me added privacy too.

On arrival to the emergency department they called my deadname. The triage nurse however knows me very well and corrected it across all systems right away. That’s the only deadnaming since. (NHS records are well known for not keeping up with each other but it’s fixed now)

So I’m in the hospital with what is believed to be a bad infection. I’ve been in since 3am Sunday morning. My experience has been mixed but I thought I would document some highlights so far. 

TW hospitals, medical detail, etc.

A final word to the world:

It’s okay to have bad times in life. It’s okay to not know your direction in life. But if there is one thing I have learnt, it is that random moments of thought and reflection can change your entire life. Look after yourself and let others help you.

I have to thank @Llama_Steven for being the most amazing boyfriend in the world. He helped me and looked after me through my feelings on that drive home. I’ve never had that before. From anyone. 

It helped me so much. I cannot thank him enough.

I got back to my town at 4:30am. I had McDonald’s and then headed home. I climbed into bed and was totally exhausted mentally and physically having been awake at this point for around 20 hours. 

I slept like a log. It was some of the best sleep I’ve had in a while and im glad.

If you happened to see a girl crying her eyes out while driving on cruise control at 50mph on the M25 Motorway last night at about 3am.... 

Well that would have been me.

I ended up crying again most of the way home. We dealt with a lot of the open ended thoughts I’d had and some of the feelings that I wasn’t sure about. It really helped to be able to talk to someone about how I was feeling. In the moment. Not days after the moment.

Steven persuaded me to talk to him. I was going to drive home in silence, dealing with my feelings alone like I’ve always done. He persuaded me to talk on voice call while I drove home and this definitely helped so much.

We talked through some of the thoughts and feelings above.

I was going to go back but it was too cold and I think I needed to deal with the emotions I had dug up already before digging deeper. 

I got myself sorted out and drove towards the exit to unlock the gates and leave. Still with tears rolling down my face.

I spent the best part of an hour and a half sat there. Getting very cold, crying and just looking out over the amazing view. 

I then wandered back to my car to warm up. I turned the engine on and sat there, warming up, still emotional but recovering. I messaged @Llama_Steven.

Back to last night... these thoughts swirled in my head. I think it was another realisation moment, reinforcing that moment from 5-6 years ago. 

I am making a difference now. And I can do more in future. But I also need to look after myself. It is a balancing act.

There’s way more to that story but this thread is already too long and I’m already too emotional. 

I survived. 

That was around 5-6 years ago. And since then I have lived by that thought, that I, although one person, can make a huge difference to the world. I found my worth.

It was that moment that this place saved my life. I had the realisation that millions of people could be seen from this spot and I was just one person. But I could make a huge difference to those people and to the world. I could help others and make their lives better.

I visited this spot while contemplating my plan. Knowing that I was likely into my last 24 hours. I sat there for a few hours. It dawned on me that night, sat there as a teenager looking out over the world, that I could make a difference in life. I could do more to help others.

There was once a time when I was extremely suicidal. I’ve never told anyone about this. I had a plan. It involved going away for a weekend and not getting back home. It was a weekend I will always remember and is one of the reasons this place is so important to me.

I do however wonder what could have happened. And some of my life could be very different. These thoughts scared me and upset me. 

Tw for next couple of tweets about suicidal thoughts. (Note: I’m okay now)

Finally suicidal thoughts have been in my head before....

The choices I’ve made throughout recent years have been huge. They’ve changed my life and ultimately I hope made me a better person. That doesn’t mean they are all the right choices. No one can ever be sure of what path I would be on had I made a different decision.

I really would have felt more comfortable and happy had I had the chance to think about my gender identity more while at that spot. But equally looking back I am happy that I have made the choices I have and that I am working more on being myself now.

The biggest aspects were the points about gender, choices I’ve made and the suicide bit. 

Let’s start with gender. 

I have contemplated pretty much all major life decisions since 2012 at that spot. Gender is the one thing I didn’t get a chance to think about much here.

Some of the thoughts while I sat there included (tw mentions of struggles inc suicide)

- gender identity
- career choice
- sexuality
- relationships
- mental health struggles
- bullying I’ve experienced
- suicide and my darkest times
- choices I’ve made and what that means

I almost instantly broke down in tears. I knew this was likely to be my reaction but I didn’t know it would be so strong. The following hour and a half I spent sat there crying. Thinking about things and going through a very bumpy rollercoaster of emotions.

As I got there I felt the emotion well up inside me. I walked around the back of some trees and bushes and headed for the bench. A metal bench placed there with a plaque in memory of someone. I don’t remember who.

I sat down and looked out at the view.

I parked up my car in the car park nearer to my spot. I wrapped up warm as it was cold and took my bottle of water and a powerbank to charge my phone. 

As I wandered up the track in the dark with my torch on, I started to see the view.

Last night I sat in my favourite spot in the early hours of the morning. I was about to head home but needed to sit there for a bit. This is a thread of my thoughts and feelings and what happened for the following hours. 

I know it’s long but I hope it’s worth the read.
